 NEW DELHI, Mon Apr 6, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The following is a snapshot of recent developments in India's general election campaign. (The sources are mentioned in brackets) The election commission has asked Home Minister Palaniappan Chidambaram to explain why action should not be taken against him for violating a model code of conduct that prohibits ministers from announcing measures that could influence voters. Chidambaram, the opposition have charged, promised some measures to voters in Rajasthan and discussed election issues during a meeting to address security issues (All newspapers). Promises made in Bharatiya Janata Party's election manifesto would cost the state exchequer an additional $10 billion (Mint). The party has promised low taxes, a low interest rate regime, farm loan waivers, and subsidised foodstuffs. H.D. Deve Gowda, the leader of a key member of the "Third Front" that pitches itself as an alternative to the two main national alliances, has said he does not want to be the prime minister if the bloc wins power (The Hindu). Deve Gowda, a former prime minister, is the leader of the Janata Dal (United) party which has influence in the southern state of Karnataka. The issue of prime minister is a sticking point in the Third Front with several leaders within the coalition expressing their desire to hold the top 
